---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Getting Started | serial-sync"
  description="Docker-first first-success path for serial-sync."
  currentPath="/getting-started/"
>
  <div class="page">
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">Getting Started</p>
      <h1>Get from zero to one successful sync path.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        The intended runtime is Docker. Use the container path first, then keep the config and
        series authoring loop local and repeatable.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>1. Build the image</h2>
      <div class="command-block">
        <pre><code>docker build -t serial-sync .</code></pre>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>2. Create credentials and bootstrap auth</h2>
      <p>
        Use the auth profile declared in your config. Keep credentials in an env file and let the
        container perform the first login.
      </p>
      <div class="command-block">
        <pre><code>printf 'PATREON_USERNAME=%s\nPATREON_PASSWORD=%s\n' "you@example.com" "your-password" &gt; patreon.env
docker run --rm \
  --env-file ./patreon.env \
  -v serial-sync-state:/state \
  -v "$PWD/config.toml:/config/config.toml:ro" \
  serial-sync setup auth --auth-profile patreon-default</code></pre>
      </div>
      <p>
        On a headless server, use the bundled noVNC auth service instead of a host-local browser:
        `docker compose -f ./examples/docker-compose.yml --profile auth-ui up --build serial-sync-auth`
        then open `http://&lt;host&gt;:8080/vnc.html?autoconnect=true&resize=scale`.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>3. Dump paid creators into a local workspace</h2>
      <p>
        This is the authoring shortcut. Dump all paid memberships once, then refine the generated
        series file offline.
      </p>
      <div class="command-block">
        <pre><code>docker run --rm \
  --env-file ./patreon.env \
  -v serial-sync-state:/state \
  -v "$PWD/config.toml:/config/config.toml:ro" \
  -v "$PWD:/work" \
  serial-sync setup dump \
    --auth-profile patreon-default \
    --path /work/serial-sync-rule-workspace \
    --force</code></pre>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>4. Preview the series offline</h2>
      <div class="command-block">
        <pre><code>docker run --rm \
  -v "$PWD/config.toml:/config/config.toml:ro" \
  -v "$PWD/serial-sync-rule-workspace:/work" \
  serial-sync setup preview \
    --workspace /work \
    --series-file /work/series.toml \
    --show-posts</code></pre>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>5. Dry-run, then run for real</h2>
      <div class="command-block">
        <pre><code>docker run --rm \
  --env-file ./patreon.env \
  -v serial-sync-state:/state \
  -v "$PWD/config.toml:/config/config.toml:ro" \
  serial-sync run --dry-run --source example-creator</code></pre>
      </div>
      <p>
        Once the dry-run looks right, drop `--dry-run` and keep the same source and target filters.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>What success looks like</h2>
      <ul class="note-list">
        <li>The auth session is reused instead of forcing you through the browser every time.</li>
        <li>The dump workspace contains posts and a starter `series.toml` you can actually edit.</li>
        <li>The first dry-run shows the right source and the right series boundaries.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
